{
  "doc_id": "33259",
  "text": "The retinoid (visual) cycle is an enzymatic pathway that regenerates visual chromophore in vertebrates. This metabolic cycle takes place mainly in the retinal pigment epithelium (RPE), a single layer of cells adjacent to the photoreceptor outer segments. Continuous regeneration of visual chromophore is critical for detection of light, and defects in the enzymes involved in the retinoid cycle often culminate in retinal dystrophy. One of the indispensable enzymes of the visual cycle is an RPE-specific protein known as RPE65, which is the retinoid isomerase that catalyzes cleavage and isomerization of all-trans-retinyl esters to form 11-cis-retinol [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
